No matter what stage you are in your life you can always move. ☺️

Clients often come to me initially with some level of pain, postural impairment, and/or injury. The common barrier I see to their success with treatment is a lack of intentional movement in their daily life and routine. Typically this is due to either fear of further aggravation to the painful area, a lack of confidence, or “not enough time”. 

I can promise you this. Movement is always better than none when it comes to healing. You don’t need a ton of time and you don’t need to be perfect. Key things to focus on are: 

1. Staying in a comfortable range of motion (not pushing into pain) 
2. Avoid going from 0 to 100 (you know who you are 😉)
3. Seek out an experts help if needed (or a friend)

#physio #mobility #functionalmovement #wellness #postpartum

For anyone not familiar, acupressure works by stimulating blood flow throughout the body which in turn promotes muscle relaxation, endorphin release, and down regulation of the nervous system. I debated for months whether or not I really “needed” a glider for my nursery. I assumed that I would be fine just feeding her on my couch, bed, etc. After a couple months of this I began having chronic tension in my back and neck due to poor posture and alignment while feeding. 

This is when I knew I HAD to change my environment, (similar to changing your desk set up at work).

I found @nurture_and and was beyond impressed. The multiple controls for the legs, lumbar spine, and neck was something I’ve never seen. Since using this recliner I feel SO much better 🙏🏼 

If you are expecting or know someone who is, I highly recommend the Glider Plus. ☺️

Here are some tips to protect your spine while feeding your baby: 

1. Relax your shoulders 
2. Place a small towel roll or pillow behind the head or low back to help support your spine
3. Make sure your feet are supported (if you don’t have a recliner you can add a stool under your feet as needed)

Neck and shoulder pain often go hand in hand due to the close interaction of several nerves and muscles. 

Restriction in the pecs specifically is a common culprit due to its impact on posture and scapular mobility. 

Many of us experience tightness here due to prolonged sitting postures, nursing or carrying our babies, and much more. 🤳🧑‍💻👩🏽‍🍼

Try incorporating these exercises daily this month and take note of any changes to your posture, tension in the neck and shoulders, and overhead mobility. 💪🏽😅

1. Wall Pec Stretch (Adjust position of shoulder as needed - hold for roughly a minute) 

2. Wall Angel (Find a neutral pelvic position and keep ribs pulled down and in. Glide hands overhead to comfortable range. Repeat for 10 reps)

Whether you are dealing with low back pain, hip stiffness, or discomfort in your knees - mobilizing the adductors could be the 🔑

The adductors originate on the pubis and ischium (pelvic bone) and insert along the medial and posterior surface of the femur (inner thigh and knee). 🦵🏼

Because of the close relationship to the pelvis, hips, and knees maintaining mobility in the adductors can make a huge impact on our everyday movement and gait. 

Aim for roughly 8-10 reps of each movement holding each rep for a full breath prior to your next workout or run. You can also try holding the Frog stretch for 1-2 minutes following a workout if feeling more limited in this area. 

😊

Who needs this today?! 👆🏽

Three simple, yet very effective ways to mobilize the neck. As always remember that stretching should feel nice and gentle. Do not yank on your head (please ☺️), instead guide your head into the stretch until a light tension is felt. 

I like to hold each of these for 3-4 breaths. 😌

Share with a friend in need of this today 🙏🏼

These two movements coupled together feel great for the thoracic spine and chest 👏🏽 

I know for me the combination of carrying my baby, doing computer work, and driving can cause these areas to get stiff. Both of these movements are great to incorporate on a regular basis to help combat pain and restrictions in range of motion through the thoracic spine, neck, and shoulders ☺️

1. Side Lying Windmill: Aim for about 6-8 reps. Keep the hips stacked. 

2. Thoracic Extension: Focus on the mid and upper back, gently extending back until light stretch is felt. Work your way up and down the spine for a couple of minutes. 

#midbackpainrelief #posture #mobility
